
This work shows the statistical analysis on sloving some genetic problems, such as detecting Mendelian Inconsistency due to potential genotyping error in every genetic marker for every offspring, performing gene association test using the cleaned genotype data generated from offspring, and identifing genetic markers that are associated with weight adjusting for faid and sex.

### 1 Setup Dataset

Dataset is avaliable at <https://github.com/xiranwang7/Genetic-Analysis>.

Data Description:
faid: Father's ID (0 indicates founder)
moid: Mother's ID (0 indicates founder)
iid: Individual ID
sex: M: male, F: Female
weight: weight
m11: the first allele in m1 marker
m12: the second allele in m1 marker
*Assume parents' genotypes are correct.*

``` r
hdata <- read.table(file="hdata.txt", header=T, sep='\t')

kable(hdata) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = F) %>%
  scroll_box(width = "100%", height = "200px")
```

``` r
offsprings <- hdata[12:nrow(hdata),]
parents    <- hdata[1:11,]
```

### 2. Detect the Mendelian inconsistency

``` r
m <- seq(6,14,2) 

intersec<-matrix(NA,nrow(offsprings),length(m))

for (i in 1:nrow(offsprings)) {
  for (j in  1:length(m)) {
    offspring_gene<-   offsprings[i,m[j]:(m[j]+1) ] 
    offspring_F<- offsprings[i,1]
    F_gene <- parents[ parents['iid']==offspring_F, m[j]:(m[j]+1) ] 
    intersec[i,j]<- length(intersect( F_gene , offspring_gene ))
  }
  }
```

Mendelian inconsistency: 1st and 10th row.

``` r
which(intersec ==0, arr.ind = T) 
```

    ##      row col
    ## [1,]   1   1
    ## [2,]  10   5

``` r
consistency <- offsprings[-c(1,10),] # Remove the Mendelian inconsistency

#kable(consistency) %>%
#  kable_styling(full_width = F) %>%
#  scroll_box(width = "100%", height = "200px")
```

### 3. Get a clean dataset

Remove offsprings with Mendelian inconsistency, and create genotype data.

``` r
m <- seq(6,14,2) 
tep_consistency <- as.matrix(consistency)
ss <- matrix(NA,nrow = nrow(consistency),5)

for (i in 1:nrow(tep_consistency)) {
  for (j in  1:length(m)) {
    consistency_gene<-  sort( tep_consistency[i,m[j]:(m[j]+1) ] )
    ss[i,j]<-paste(  consistency_gene[1],"_",consistency_gene[2] )
    #tep_consistency[i, m[j]: (m[j]+1) ]<- c( consistency_gene[1],consistency_gene[2] )
  }
}
sort_consistency<-data.frame(consistency[,1:4],as.numeric ( (as.vector(consistency[,5]) ) ),ss)
colnames(sort_consistency)<-c('faid','moid','iid','sex','weight','M1','M2','M3','M4','M5')

kable(sort_consistency[1:10,]) %>%
  kable_styling( ) %>%
  scroll_box(width = "500px" , height = "200px")
```

### 4.2 Investigate more by fitting a linear regresion

Tired to fit M1-M5 with faid and sex, based on p-vlaue for each valiable, M5 is genetic markers that are associated with weight adjusting for faid and sex.In addition, based on summary(fitM5), M1 allele in M5 marker increases weight, so it is apporiate to make a dummy variable for ensuring this. Based on fitM5M1,M1 in M5 marker increases weight by 15.7683 on average, hold the other variables unchange.

``` r
fitM5 <- lm(weight ~ factor(faid) + factor( sex)+ M5, data = sort_consistency)
summary(fitM5)
```
